explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is used twice at the start of the function. Its expansion controls control-flow (it may perform a conditional return, call an abort routine, or do nothing). To determine whether any later statements in the function can be unreachable you must see the exact macro definition/expansion.
- OS_ObjectIdFindByName: The function called to obtain the id is assigned to return_code. If this callee is declared/implemented with non-returning behavior (e.g. noreturn, infinite loop, abort) then the subsequent "return return_code;" (or any code after the call) could be unreachable. The callee's prototype/definition/attributes are required to decide reachability.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: This macro/constant is passed to OS_ObjectIdFindByName; its resolution is needed when inspecting the implementation of OS_ObjectIdFindByName (it may change internal behavior or select code paths that do not return).
- OS_printf: Appears in the static call graph for this function (via macros/test stubs). If OS_CHECK_POINTER expands to calls to OS_printf that affect control flow (e.g. print then abort), the precise behavior is needed to judge reachability.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test stub/registration helpers show up in the static call graph and are commonly invoked inside the OS_CHECK_POINTER / related test-macros. Their implementations may call abort/assert functions or perform unconditional returns; therefore their definitions are required to determine whether the macro-expanded code can make paths unreachable.
- UtAssert_Abort: Shown as being called by the UT stub helpers. If any macro or UT helper invokes UtAssert_Abort (a non-returning abort), that produces unreachable code after the call; so its behavior/attributes (noreturn or not) must be known.

Note: The above list targets all symbols that can alter control-flow (conditional/unconditional returns, aborts, infinite loops) when the macros in this function are expanded. Other basic types (int32, osal_id_t) are not required to assess reachability.
